Check out the [code here](https://github.com/sebastianbergmann/phpunit/blob/cd13b23ac5a519a4708e00736c26ee0bb28b2e01/src/Util/Configuration.php#L541-L548). Specifically the call to [`putenv`](http://php.net/manual/en/function.putenv.php). `putenv` only takes a string, and the code in PHPUnit just concatenates the name and value directly.

If checking the truthiness or falsiness doesn't work for you, use [`$_ENV`](http://php.net/manual/en/reserved.variables.environment.php) instead. Or run the value through filter var and validate it as a boolean.

``` php
if (filter_var(getenv('FOO'), FILTER_VALIDATE_BOOLEAN)) {
  // ...
}
```

For those finding this issue currently, I created a workaround like so:
```xml
        <env name="AUTHORISATION_ENABLED" value="0" force="true" />
```
Then converted the value like so:
```php
$enabled = env('AUTHORISATION_ENABLED', true);

if ($enabled === '0') {
    $enabled = false;
} elseif ($enabled === '1') {
    $enabled = true;
}

return 'enabled' => $enabled;
```
I needed a custom configuration setting in a Laravel application derived from an environment variable. Strings worked fine so I used 0/1 as true/false. Granted I probably could have used `parseInt()` but I wanted to be explicit about the values I was converting.
